'''Nathan Jackson''' (born August 29, 1938<ref name=nea/>) is an American artist. He is among the most important living [[Tlingit people|Tlingit]] artists<ref>{{cite web|title=Contemporary artists: Tlingit|url=http://www.amnh.org/exhibitions/totems/contemporary/tlingit.php|publisher=[[American Museum of Natural History]]|accessdate=April 2, 2011}}</ref> and the most important [[Alaska]]n artists.<ref name=je>{{cite news|last=Dunham|first=Mike|title=Tlingit 'peace' headpiece now in Juneau museum|url=http://juneauempire.com/stories/083110/loc_702538776.shtml|newspaper=[[Juneau Empire]]|date=August 31, 2010}}</ref> He is best known for his [[totem pole]]s, but works in a variety of media.

Jackson belongs to the Sockeye [[Tlingit clans|clan]] on the Raven side of the Chilkoot Tlingit.<ref name=nea/> As a young adult, he served in the military in [[Germany]], and then became involved in commercial fishing.<ref name=nea/> While ill with [[pneumonia]] and unable to fish, he began to carve miniature totem poles.<ref name=nea/> His interest in art was piqued, and he enrolled in the [[Institute of American Indian Arts]] in [[Santa Fe, New Mexico|Santa Fe]], [[New Mexico]].<ref name=nea/> Since then, Jackson's work has included large totem poles, canoes, carved doors, wood panel clan crests, masks, and jewelry.<ref name=nea/> Jackson has worked to pass on traditional Tlingit carving skills to younger artists, and has offered many demonstrations and workshops in Alaska and the Pacific Northwest.<ref name=nea/>

Jackson has created more than 50 totem poles,<ref name=via>{{cite news|last=Rennicke|first=Jeff|title=Totem poles|url=http://www.viamagazine.com/attractions/totem-poles|newspaper=[[Via]]|date=May/June 2008}}</ref> some of which are on display in the [[National Museum of the American Indian]],<ref>{{cite web|title=Kaats (depicting the story of a man who lived with a bear family)|url=http://www.nmai.si.edu/searchcollections/item.aspx?irn=280007&catids=0&areaid=16&src=1-1&size=75&page=12|publisher=[[National Museum of the American Indian]]|accessdate=April 2, 2011}}</ref>  the [[Field Museum]] in Chicago,<ref name=field>{{cite news|title=Field Museum's new totem pole erected|url=http://www.msnbc.msn.com/id/17919655/ns/travel-destination_travel/|newspaper=MSNBC.com (Associated Press)|date=April 2, 2007}}</ref> [[Harvard University]]'s [[Peabody Museum of Archaeology and Ethnology|Peabody Museum]],<ref>{{cite web|title=NAGPRA in the Museum GalleriesNAGPRA in the Museum Galleries|url=http://www.peabody.harvard.edu/node/313|publisher=[[Peabody Museum of Archaeology and Ethnology]]|accessdate=April 2, 2011}}</ref> and other museums in the United States, Europe, and Japan.<ref name=nea/> Other totem poles stand outside [[Juneau Douglas High School]],<ref name=list/> Juneau's [[Centennial Hall]],<ref name=list/><ref name="Stewart1993">{{cite book|author=Hilary Stewart|title=Looking at totem poles|url=http://books.google.com/books?id=WSueEr81v0IC&pg=PA183|date=1993|publisher=Douglas & McIntyre|isbn=978-1-55054-074-1|pages=183}}</ref> in Juneau's [[Sealaska]] Building,<ref name=list>{{cite news|title=A list of local totem poles|url=http://juneauempire.com/stories/082610/art_700570930.shtml|newspaper=[[Juneau Empire]]|date=August 26, 2010}}</ref> in [[Totem Bight State Historical Park]],<ref>{{cite web|title=Totem Poles at Totem Bight State Historical Park|url=http://dnr.alaska.gov/parks/units/totempol.htm|publisher=Alaska Division of Parks and Outdoor Recreation|accessdate=April 2, 2011}}</ref> at the [[Alaska Native Heritage Center]],<ref name=je/> at [[Saxman Totem Park]],<ref>{{cite news|last=Holing|first=Dwight|title=Totems speak of another way|url=http://news.google.com/newspapers?id=0mUaAAAAIBAJ&sjid=iCoEAAAAIBAJ&pg=6877,4938021|newspaper=[[Milwaukee Journal]]|date=February 22, 1987|page=H1}}</ref> and at the [[Totem Heritage Center]] in [[Ketchikan]].<ref name="Stewart1993">{{cite book|author=Hilary Stewart|title=Looking at totem poles|url=http://books.google.com/books?id=WSueEr81v0IC&pg=PA171|date=1993|publisher=Douglas & McIntyre|isbn=978-1-55054-074-1|pages=171}}</ref>  He is a recipient of a [[National Endowment for the Arts]] [[National Heritage Fellowship]] (1995),<ref name=nea>{{cite web|title=Nathan Jackson|url=http://www.nea.gov/honors/heritage/fellows/fellow.php?id=1995_07&type=bio|publisher=[[National Endowment for the Arts]]|accessdate=April 2, 2011}}</ref> a [[Rasmuson Foundation]] Distinguished Artist Award (2009),<ref name=rasmuson>{{cite web|last=Stalzer|first=Cassandra|title=Nathan Jackson receives $25,000 Distinguished Artist Award; Foundation Also Names Eight Fellows, 17 Project Grants|url=http://www.rasmuson.org/PressRelease/index.php?switch=view_pressrelease&iReleaseID=206|publisher=[[Rasmuson Foundation]]|accessdate=April 2, 2011|date=May 15, 2009}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Dunham|first=Mike|title=Rasmuson Grants are announced|url=http://www.adn.com/2009/05/16/798087/rasmuson-grants-are-announced.html|newspaper=[[Anchorage Daily News]]|date=May 16th, 2009}}</ref> and an honorary doctorate in humanities from the [[University of Alaska Southeast]].<ref name=nea/>

Jackson currently resides in Ketchikan, Alaska.<ref>{{cite news|title=Nathan Jackson receives $25,000 Distinguished Artist Award|url=http://www.capitalcityweekly.com/stories/052009/new_442015051.shtml|accessdate=April 3, 2011|newspaper=[[Capital City Weekly]]|date=May 20, 2009}}</ref> His wife and son are also artists.<ref name=field/>

